fields.description: Nambi Narayanan

fields.name: SAM ALTMAN
fields.description: Sam Altman is an American entrepreneur, investor, and programmer. He is the co-founder and CEO of OpenAI, a non-profit research company that promotes and develops friendly artificial intelligence. He was previously the president of Y Combinator, a startup accelerator.

fields.name: Peter Thiel
fields.description: Peter Andreas Thiel (born October 11, 1967) is a German-American billionaire entrepreneur, venture capitalist, and political activist. A co-founder of PayPal, Palantir Technologies, and Founders Fund, he was the first outside investor in Facebook. As of March 2023, Thiel had an estimated net worth of $9.55 billion and was ranked 215th on the Bloomberg Billionaires Index.

fields.name: Satya Nadella
fields.description: Satya Narayana Nadella is an Indian-American business executive. He is the executive chairman and CEO of Microsoft, succeeding Steve Ballmer in 2014 as CEO and John W. Thompson in 2021 as chairman.

fields.name: Sam Bankman-Fried
fields.description: Sam Bankman-Fried is an American entrepreneur, investor, and alleged fraudster. He was the founder and CEO of the cryptocurrency exchange FTX and associated trading firm Alameda Research, both of which experienced a high-profile collapse resulting in Chapter 11 bankruptcy in late 2022.

fields.name: Demis Hassabis
fields.description: Emos Hassabis is a British neuroscientist, game designer, and entrepreneur. He is the co-founder and CEO of DeepMind, a British artificial intelligence research company acquired by Google in 2014. Hassabis is also the co-founder of Elixir Studios, a video game development company.

fields.name: Elizabeth Holmes
fields.description: Elizabeth Holmes was a former biotechnology entrepreneur who founded Theranos, a company that claimed to have revolutionized blood testing by developing methods that needed only very small volumes of blood, such as from a fingerprick. In 2015, Forbes had named Holmes the youngest and wealthiest self-made female billionaire in the United States on the basis of a $9-billion valuation of her company.

fields.name: Narayan Murthy
fields.description: Narayana Murthy is an Indian billionaire businessman and the co-founder of Infosys, a multinational information technology company. He is considered to be one of the pioneers of the Indian IT industry and is credited with helping to transform India into a global hub for IT services.

fields.name: nandan nilekani
fields.description: Nandan Nilekani is an Indian businessman and politician. He is the co-founder of Infosys, a multinational information technology company. He served as the chairman of the Unique Identification Authority of India (UIDAI) from 2009 to 2014. He is a member of the Rajya Sabha, the upper house of the Indian Parliament, representing the state of Karnataka.

fields.name: virat kohli
fields.description:
Virat Kohli is an Indian international cricketer who captains the Indian national team in all formats. He is a right-handed top-order batsman who is widely regarded as one of the best batsmen in the world.

Kohli made his international debut for India in 2008 and has since established himself as one of the most prolific batsmen in the history of the game. He holds the record for the fastest batsman to score 8,000, 9,000, 10,000, 11,000, 12,000, and 13,000 runs in ODI cricket. He is also the fastest batsman to score 20 centuries in ODI cricket.

fields.name: sachin tendulkar
fields.description: Sachin Ramesh Tendulkar is a former international cricketer who captained the Indian national team. He is widely regarded as one of the greatest batsmen in the history of cricket. He is the all-time highest run-scorer in both ODI and Test cricket with more than 18,000 runs and 15,000 runs, respectively. He also holds the record for receiving the most man-of-the-match awards in international cricket.

fields.name: ms dhoni
fields.description: Mahendra Singh Dhoni is an former Indian cricketer. He was captain of the Indian national team in limited-overs formats from 2007 to 2017 and in Test cricket from 2008 to 2014. He plays as a right-handed wicket-keeper-batsman and is also the current captain of Chennai Super Kings in the Indian Premier League.

fields.name: Lionel Messi
fields.description: Lionel Andrés Messi is an Argentine professional footballer who plays as a forward for Ligue 1 club Paris Saint-Germain and captains the Argentina national team.

fields.name: Steve Blank
fields.description: Steve Blank

fields.name: Simon Sinek
fields.description: Simon Sinek is a British-American author, motivational speaker, and organizational consultant, who is best known for popularizing the "Golden Circle" concept. He is the author of five books, including Start with Why (2009), Leaders Eat Last (2011), Together is Better (2014), Find Your Why (2017), and The Infinite Game (2019).

fields.name: Eric Schmidt
fields.description: Eric Schmidt is an American business executive and software engineer who served as the CEO of Google from 2001 to 2011 and the company's executive chairman from 2011 to 2015, as executive chairman of parent company Alphabet Inc. from 2015 to 2017, and Technical Advisor at Alphabet from 2017 to 2020. He is the co-founder of Innovation Endeavors, a venture capital firm that has invested in Uber, SoFi, and Zymergen, among others.

fields.name: Robin Sharma
fields.description: Robin Sharma is a Canadian self-help author who is best known for his books The Monk Who Sold His Ferrari and The 5 AM Club. He has written over 25 books, which have sold over 100 million copies worldwide. Sharma is a popular speaker and has given keynote presentations to Fortune 500 companies and organizations around the world.

fields.name: varun grover
fields.description: arun Grover is an Indian writer, comedian, poet, and filmmaker. He is best known for his work in Hindi cinema, where he has written lyrics, dialogues, and screenplays for films such as Gangs of Wasseypur, Masaan, and Article 15. He has also written for television shows such as The Great Indian Comedy Show and Aisi Taisi Democracy. In 2015, he won the National Film Award for Best Lyricist for his work on the film Masaan.

fields.name: Aman Gupta
fields.description: Aman Gupta was born on Thursday, 4 March 1982 (age 41 years; as of 2023) in New Delhi. His zodiac sign is Pisces. He completed his schooling at Delhi Public School, R. K. Puram, New Delhi. Later, he attended Shaheed Bhagat Singh College (M) from 1998 to 2001 to study Bachelor of Commerce (Hons.) He pursued Chartered Accountant, Accounting and Finance at the Institute of Chartered Accountants of India from 1999 to 2002.

fields.name: Peyush Bansal
fields.description:
Peyush Bansal is an Indian entrepreneur and the CEO and co-founder of Lenskart, an online eyewear retailer. He is also a judge on the Indian version of the reality TV show Shark Tank.

Bansal was born in Delhi, India, in 1981. He studied engineering at McGill University in Montreal, Canada, and then worked as a management consultant at McKinsey & Company. In 2007, he co-founded Lenskart with his friends Amit Chaudhary and Anant Goenka.

fields.name: Anupam Mittal
fields.description:
Anupam Mittal is an Indian billionaire businessman and the founder and former CEO of Shaadi.com, one of the largest online matrimonial services in the world. He is also a judge on the Indian version of the reality TV show Shark Tank.

Mittal was born in Ludhiana, Punjab, India, in 1967. He studied engineering at the Indian Institute of Technology Delhi and then worked as a management consultant at McKinsey & Company. In 1997, he co-founded Shaadi.com with his wife, Anurita Mittal.

fields.name: Ashneer Grover
fields.description: Indian businessman Ashneer Grover is the former co-founder and managing director of the Indian fintech company BharatPe. Grover also appears as an investor on the reality TV show Shark Tank India. Find Ashneer online: Twitter:

fields.name: Vineeta Vingh
fields.description: Vineeta Singh is an Indian entrepreneur and CEO and co-founder of Sugar Cosmetics. She has been a shark on the business reality TV show Shark Tank India since the show started airing on SonyLIV in 2021

fields.name: Ghazal Alagh
fields.description: A Corporate trainer turned artist cum entrepreneur Ghazal Alagh, co-founded Mamaearth, driven by the passion for making early parenting, stress-free. As the Co-Founder and Chief Mama at Mamaearth, India's first toxin-free baby care brand, Ghazal is responsible for product development and community management.

fields.name: Namita Thapar
fields.description: Namita Thapar, one of India's leading businesswomen, is the CEO of Emcure Pharmaceuticals, an Indian multinational pharmaceutical company based in Pune, Maharashtra. She is one of the titular sharks on the popular TV show Shark Tank, and her popularity has skyrocketed since the show came out.

fields.name: Amitabh Bachchan
fields.description: Amitabh Bachchan is an Indian actor, film producer, television host, occasional playback singer and former politician, who works in Hindi cinema. In film career spanning over five decades, he has starred in more than 200 films

fields.name: Andrew Ng
fields.description: Andrew Yan-Tak Ng is a British-born American computer scientist and technology entrepreneur focusing on machine learning and artificial intelligence.

fields.name: Jocko Willink
fields.description: John Gretton "Jocko" Willink is an American author, podcaster, and retired United States Navy officer who served in the Navy SEALs and is a former member of SEAL Team 3

fields.name: Stewart Brand
fields.description: Stewart Brand is an American writer, best known as the editor of the Whole Earth Catalog. He founded a number of organizations, including The WELL, the Global Business Network, and the Long Now Foundation. He is the author of several books, most recently Whole Earth Discipline: An Ecopragmatist Manifesto

fields.name: Ray Dalio
fields.description: Raymond Thomas Dalio is an American billionaire investor and hedge fund manager, who has served as co-chief investment officer of the world's largest hedge fund, Bridgewater Associates, since 1985. He founded Bridgewater in 1975 in New York.

fields.name: J.K. Rowling
fields.description: Joanne Rowling CH OBE FRSL, best known by her pen name J. K. Rowling, is a British author and philanthropist. She wrote Harry Potter, a seven-volume children's fantasy series published from 1997 to 2007.

fields.name: Melinda Gates
fields.description: Melinda French Gates is an American philanthropist, former multimedia product developer and manager at Microsoft, and the ex-wife of its co-founder and billionaire Bill Gates. French Gates has consistently been ranked as one of the world's most powerful women by Forbes magazine.

fields.name: Melinda Gates
fields.description: Melinda French Gates is an American philanthropist, former multimedia product developer and manager at Microsoft, and the ex-wife of its co-founder and billionaire Bill Gates. French Gates has consistently been ranked as one of the world's most powerful women by Forbes magazine.

fields.name: Balaji Srinivasan
fields.description: Balaji S. Srinivasan is an American entrepreneur and investor. He was the co-founder of Counsyl, the former Chief Technology Officer of Coinbase, and former general partner at the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz.

fields.name: Dwayne Johnson
fields.description: Dwayne Douglas Johnson, is an American actor, film producer, and former professional wrestler known by the ring name The Rock.

fields.name: Greta Thunberg
fields.description: Greta Tintin Eleonora Ernman Thunberg is a Swedish environmental activist who is known for challenging world leaders to take immediate action for climate change mitigation. Thunberg's activism began when she persuaded her parents to adopt lifestyle choices that reduced their own carbon footprint

fields.name: Mark Cuban
fields.description: Mark Cuban is an American businessman, film producer, investor, philanthropist, television personality, and writer who is the owner of the Dallas Mavericks and co-owner of 2929 Entertainment. He is also one of the main "sharks" on the ABC reality television series Shark Tank.

fields.name: Jeff Atwood
fields.description: Jeff Atwood is an American software developer, author, blogger, and entrepreneur. He co-founded the computer programming question-and-answer website Stack Overflow and co-founded Stack Exchange, which extends Stack Overflow's question-and-answer model to subjects other than programming.

fields.name: Charlie Munger
fields.description: Charles Thomas Munger is an American businessman, investor, and philanthropist. He is vice chairman of Berkshire Hathaway, the conglomerate controlled by Warren Buffett; Buffett has described Munger as his closest partner and right-hand man.

fields.name: Dustin Moskovitz
fields.description: Dustin Aaron Moskovitz is an American Internet entrepreneur who co-founded Facebook, Inc. with Mark Zuckerberg, Eduardo Saverin, Andrew McCollum, and Chris Hughes. In 2008, he left Facebook to co-found Asana with Justin Rosenstein.

fields.name: Mr. Money Mustache
fields.description: Mr. Money Mustache is the website and pseudonym of 48-year-old Canadian-born blogger Peter Adeney. Adeney retired from his job as a software engineer in 2005 at age 30 by spending only a small percentage of his annual salary and consistently investing the remainder, primarily in stock market index funds.

fields.name: Lex Fridman
fields.description: Lex Fridman is a Russian-American computer scientist, podcaster, and artificial intelligence researcher. He is a research scientist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and he hosts the Lex Fridman Podcast, a podcast and YouTube series.

fields.name: LARRY ELLISON
fields.description: Lawrence Joseph Ellison is an American business magnate and investor. He is the co-founder, executive chairman, chief technology officer, and former chief executive officer of the American computer technology company Oracle Corporation.

fields.name: KANYE WEST
fields.description: Born in Atlanta and raised in Chicago,[5][6] West gained recognition as a producer for Roc-A-Fella Records in the early 2000s, producing singles for several artists and developing the "chipmunk soul" sampling style.

fields.name: TIM FERRISS
fields.description: Timothy Ferriss is an American entrepreneur, investor, author, podcaster, and lifestyle guru. He became well-known through his 4-Hour self-help book series—including The 4-Hour Work Week, The 4-Hour Body, and The 4-Hour Chef—that focused on lifestyle optimizations, but he has since reconsidered this approach.

fields.name: SETH GODIN
fields.description: Seth Godin is an American author, entrepreneur, and marketer. He is the author of 20 books, including the bestsellers "The Dip," "Linchpin," and "Purple Cow." He is also the founder of the marketing blog Squidoo and the online learning platform Akimbo.

fields.name: VINOD KHOSLA
fields.description: Vinod Khosla is an Indian-American businessman and venture capitalist. He is a co-founder of Sun Microsystems and the founder of Khosla Ventures. Khosla made his wealth from early venture capital investments in areas such as networking, software, and alternative energy technologies.

fields.name: TONY ROBBINS
fields.description:
Robbins was born in North Hollywood, California, in 1960. He began his career as a salesman, but he soon realized that his true passion was helping people. In 1988, he founded his own company, Tony Robbins International, which offers a variety of self-help programs and products.

Robbins has written six books, including the bestsellers "Unleash the Power Within" and "Awaken the Giant Within." His seminars have been attended by some of the world's most successful people, including Bill Clinton, Oprah Winfrey, and Leonardo DiCaprio.

fields.name: ANDREW WILKINSON
fields.description:
Andrew Wilkinson is a Canadian venture capitalist and entrepreneur.
He is the co-founder of Tiny Capital, a venture capital firm that invests in early-stage internet companies.
He is also the co-founder of Dribbble, a social media platform for designers.
Wilkinson is a graduate of the University of Victoria, where he studied computer science.
He began his career as a software engineer at Microsoft.
In 2006, he co-founded Dribbble with his friend Dan Cederholm.
Dribbble quickly became a popular platform for designers to share their work.

fields.name: Bernard Arnault
fields.description: Bernard Jean Étienne Arnault is a French business magnate, investor, and art collector. He is the founder, chairman, and chief executive officer of LVMH Moët Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the world's largest luxury goods company.

fields.name: Sergey Brin
fields.description:
Sergey Brin is a Russian-American computer scientist and internet entrepreneur.
He is best known as one of the co-founders of Google, along with Larry Page.
Brin was born in Moscow, Russia, in 1973.
He and his family emigrated to the United States in 1979.
Brin attended the University of Maryland, College Park, where he received a bachelor's degree in mathematics and computer science.

fields.name: Winston Churchill
fields.description:
Sir Winston Leonard Spencer-Churchill (30 November 1874 – 24 January 1965) was a British statesman, soldier, writer, and artist who served as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom from 1940 to 1945, during the Second World War, and again from 1951 to 1955.
Apart from two years between 1922 and 1924, he was a Member of Parliament (MP) from 1900 to 1964 and represented a total of five constituencies.

fields.name: kim kardashian
fields.description:
Kim Kardashian is an American reality TV star, businesswoman, and socialite.
She is best known for her appearances on the reality TV series Keeping Up with the Kardashians.
Kardashian was born in Los Angeles, California, in 1980.
She is the daughter of Kris Jenner and Robert Kardashian, a lawyer who was one of O.J. Simpson's defense attorneys.

fields.name: Rihanna
fields.description:
Robyn Rihanna Fenty is a Barbadian singer, actress, and businesswoman.
She was born in Saint Michael, Barbados, on February 20, 1988.
She began her career in music in 2003 when she signed a recording contract with Def Jam Recordings.
Her debut album, Music of the Sun, was released in 2005 and was a commercial success.
Her subsequent albums, A Girl Like Me (2006), Good Girl Gone Bad (2007), and Rated R (2009), were also successful, and she became one of the best-selling music artists of all time.
Rihanna has also starred in several films, including Bring It On: All or Nothing (2006), Battleship (2012), and Ocean's 8 (2018).

fields.name: Gal Gadot
fields.description:
Gal Gadot is an Israeli actress and model.
She was born in Petah Tikva, Israel, on April 30, 1985.
She was crowned Miss Israel in 2004 and represented her country at the Miss Universe 2004 pageant.
Gadot then served in the Israel Defense Forces for two years as a combat fitness instructor.
After her military service, Gadot began studying law and international relations at IDC Herzliya.
However, she left her studies to pursue a career in modeling and acting.
Gadot's first international film performance was as Gisele Yashar in Fast & Furious (2009), a part she reprised in the sequels Fast Five (2011), Fast & Furious 6 (2013), and Fast X (2023).
Gadot went on to achieve global stardom for her portrayal of Wonder Woman in the DC Extended Universe, including Wonder Woman (2017) and Wonder Woman 1984 (2020).

fields.name: priyanka chopra
fields.description:
Priyanka Chopra Jonas (née Chopra) is an Indian actress, singer, and producer.
She was born on July 18, 1982, in Jamshedpur, India.
She began her career as a model and won the Miss World 2000 pageant.
Chopra then moved to Mumbai to pursue a career in acting.
She made her Bollywood debut in the 2002 film The Hero: Love Story of a Spy.
Chopra has since starred in over 50 films, including Barfi! (2012), Mary Kom (2014), and Bajirao Mastani (2015).
She has also appeared in several American films, including Baywatch (2017) and Isn't It Romantic (2019).

fields.name: Dua Lipa
fields.description:
Dua Lipa is an English singer and songwriter.
She was born in London, England, on August 22, 1995.
Her parents are Kosovan Albanians who fled the Kosovo War in 1992.
Lipa began her music career in 2015, when she signed with Warner Music Group.
Her self-titled debut album was released in 2017 and was a critical and commercial success.
The album spawned the hit singles "New Rules", "IDGAF", and "Be the One".

fields.name: Alia Bhatt
fields.description:
Alia Bhatt is an Indian actress and singer who works in Hindi films.
She was born on March 15, 1993, in Mumbai, Maharashtra, India.
She is the daughter of filmmaker Mahesh Bhatt and actress Soni Razdan.
Bhatt made her acting debut in the 2012 film Student of the Year, for which she won the Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut.

fields.name: Deepika Padukone
fields.description:
Deepika Padukone is an Indian actress who works predominantly in Hindi films.
She was born on 5 January 1986 in Copenhagen, Denmark, to Indian parents Prakash Padukone and Ujjala Padukone.
Her father is a former badminton champion and her mother is a homemaker.
Padukone has a younger sister, Anisha.
She studied at Sophia High School in Bangalore and then went on to study mass communication at Mount Carmel College.

fields.name: katrina kaif
fields.description: Katrina Kaif is a British actress who works in Hindi-language films. One of the highest-paid actresses in India, she has received accolades, including four Screen Awards and four Zee Cine Awards, in addition to 3 Filmfare nominations.

fields.name: Tom Holland
fields.description: Thomas Stanley Holland is an English actor. His accolades include a British Academy Film Award and three Saturn Awards. Some publications have called him one of the most popular actors of his generation.

fields.name: Gary Vaynerchuk
fields.description: Gary Vaynerchuk, commonly known as Gary Vee, is an American entrepreneur, author, speaker, and Internet personality. He is a co-founder of the restaurant reservation software company Resy and Empathy Wines.

fields.name: Grant Cardone
fields.description: Grant Cardone is a world-renowned entrepreneur, author, speaker, investor, and coach. He owns and operates seven privately held companies, and a private equity real estate firm, Cardone Capital, with a multifamily portfolio of assets worth over $4 Billion.

fields.name: Brené Brown
fields.description: Casandra Brené Brown is an American professor, author, and podcast host. Brown is known for her work on shame, vulnerability, and leadership, and for her widely viewed TEDx talk in 2010. She has written six number-one New York Times bestselling books and hosted two podcasts on Spotify.

fields.name: Dave Ramsey
fields.description:
Dave Ramsey is an American radio personality, author, and businessman.
He is best known for his advice on personal finance and his 7 Baby Steps to Financial Peace.
Ramsey is the host of The Dave Ramsey Show, a nationally syndicated radio show that is heard by over 18 million people each week.
He is also the author of several books, including The Total Money Makeover, Financial Peace Revisited, and EntreLeadership.
Ramsey is the founder of Ramsey Solutions, a company that provides financial education and resources to people all over the world.

fields.name: Daymond John
fields.description: Daymond Garfield John is an American businessman, investor, and television personality. He is best known as the founder, president, and chief executive officer of FUBU, and appears as an investor on the ABC reality television series Shark Tank. Based in New York City, John is the founder of The Shark Group

fields.name: Steven Bartlett
fields.description: Steven Cliff Bartlett is a British-Nigerian entrepreneur and podcaster. He is the co-founder of Thirdweb, Flight Story and Flight Story Fund. He was the co-founder and co-CEO of Social Chain, however, he stepped down from the latter role in December 2020

fields.name: Brendon Burchard
fields.description: Brendon Burchard is a New York Times bestselling author. His latest book, High-Performance Habits, was a Wall Street Journal bestseller and was nominated by Amazon as one of his top three businesses and

fields.name: Russell Brunson
fields.description: Russell Brunson started his first online company while he was wrestling in college. Within a year of graduation, he had sold over a million dollars of his own products and services from his basement.

fields.name: Marc Andreessen
fields.description: Marc Lowell Andreessen is an American entrepreneur, venture capital investor, and software engineer. He is the co-author of Mosaic, the first widely used web browser with a graphical user interface; co-founder of Netscape; and co-founder and general partner of Silicon Valley venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz.

fields.name: Neil Patel
fields.description:
Neil Patel is a digital marketing consultant, entrepreneur, and investor.

He is the co-founder of Crazy Egg, Hello Bar, and KISSmetrics.

He is also the author of the book "Hacking Growth: How Today's Fastest-Growing Companies Drive Traction."**

fields.name: Matthew Walker
fields.description: Matthew Paul Walker is an English scientist and professor of neuroscience and psychology at the University of California, Berkeley. He is a public intellectual focused on the subject of sleep. As an academic, Walker has focused on the impact of sleep on human health

fields.name: Vaclav Smil
fields.description: Vaclav Smil is a Czech-Canadian scientist and policy analyst. He is a Distinguished Professor Emeritus in the Faculty of Environment at the University of Manitoba in Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada

fields.name: Max Tegmark
fields.description: Max Erik Tegmark is a Swedish-American physicist, cosmologist, and machine learning researcher. He is a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the president of the Future of Life Institute.

fields.name: Barack Obama
fields.description: Barack Hussein Obama II is an American politician who served as the 44th president of the United States from 2009 to 2017. A member of the Democratic Party, he was the first African-American president of the United States

fields.name: Keith Rabois
fields.description:
Keith Rabois is an American technology executive and investor.
He is currently a general partner at Founders Fund.
He is widely known for his early-stage startup investments and his executive roles at PayPal, LinkedIn, Slide, and Square (now known as Block, Inc.).

fields.name: PewDiePie
fields.description:
PewDiePie, whose real name is Felix Arvid Ulf Kjellberg, is a Swedish YouTuber and comedian.
He is known for his Let's Play videos and comedic formatted videos and shows.
Kjellberg's popularity on YouTube and extensive media coverage have made him one of the most noted online personalities and content creators.

fields.name: Carl von Clausewitz
fields.description:
Carl Philipp Gottlieb von Clausewitz was a Prussian military theorist and general.
He is considered one of the most influential military thinkers in history.
His most famous work is On War, which is a treatise on the nature of war and its relationship to politics.

fields.name: Nick Bostrom
fields.description:
Nick Bostrom is a Swedish philosopher and futurist.
He is a professor at the University of Oxford, where he is the founding director of the Future of Humanity Institute.

fields.name: Naomi Oreskes,
fields.description: There is no book called "Superintelligence" by Naomi Oreskes. However, there is a book called Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies by Nick Bostrom.

fields.name: Jane Austen
fields.description: Jane Austen was an English novelist who lived from 1775 to 1817. She is best known for her six major novels, which are considered classics of English literature.

fields.name: Michael Schulman
fields.description: staff writer for The New Yorker and the author of several books, including Her Again: Becoming Meryl Streep, which was a New York Times bestseller.

fields.name: Talulah Riley
fields.description: Talulah Jane Riley-Milburn is an English actress and writer. She has appeared in films, including Pride & Prejudice, St Trinian's and its sequel St Trinian's 2: The Legend of Fritton's Gold, The Boat That Rocked, and Inception.

fields.name: Ian Goodfellow,
fields.description: Ian J. Goodfellow is an American computer scientist, engineer, and executive, most noted for his work on artificial neural networks and deep learning.

fields.name: Ayn Rand
fields.description: lice O'Connor, better known by her pen name Ayn Rand, was a Russian-born American writer and philosopher. She is known for her fiction and for developing a philosophical system she named Objectivism. Born and educated in Russia, she moved to the United States in 1926.

fields.name: Samuel Beckett
fields.description: Samuel Barclay Beckett was an Irish novelist, dramatist, short story writer, theatre director, poet, and literary translator. His literary and theatrical work features bleak, impersonal, and tragicomic experiences of life, often coupled with black comedy and nonsense

fields.name: Richard Dawkins
fields.description: ichard Dawkins FRS FRSL is a British evolutionary biologist and author. He is an emeritus fellow of New College, Oxford, and was Professor for Public Understanding of Science in the University of Oxford from 1995 to 2008.

fields.name: Catherine
fields.description: Catherine II, most commonly known as Catherine the Great, was the reigning empress of Russia from 1762 to 1796. She came to power after overthrowing her husband, Peter III.

fields.name: John Green
fields.description: John Michael Green is an American author, YouTuber, podcaster, and philanthropist. His books have more than 50 million copies in print worldwide, including The Fault in Our Stars, which is one of the best-selling books of all time.

fields.name: Sam Walton
fields.description: Samuel Moore Walton was an American business magnate best known for founding the retailers Walmart and Sam's Club, which he started in 1962 and 1983 respectively.

fields.name: Michael D. Rich
fields.description: Michael D. Rich, President and CEO of the RAND Corporation.

fields.name: Melinda French Gates
fields.description: Melinda French Gates is an American philanthropist, former multimedia product developer and manager at Microsoft, and the ex-wife of its co-founder and billionaire Bill Gates.

fields.name: Mitch Landrieu
fields.description: Mitchell Joseph Landrieu is an American lawyer and politician who served as Mayor of New Orleans from 2010 to 2018. A member of the Democratic Party, he previously served as Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana from 2004 to 2010.

fields.name: Enrico Moretti
fields.description: Enrico Moretti is an Italian economist and the Michael Peevey and Donald Vial Professor of Economics at the University of California, Berkeley.

fields.name: John Doerr
fields.description: L. John Doerr is an American investor and venture capitalist at Kleiner Perkins in Menlo Park, California.

fields.name: Hans Rosling
fields.description: Hans Rosling was a Swedish physician, academic and public speaker. He was a professor of international health at Karolinska Institute and was the co-founder and chairman of the Gapminder Foundation, which developed the Trendalyzer software system.

fields.name: Patrick Deneen
fields.description: Patrick J. Deneen is a Professor of Political Science at the University of Notre Dame. He studies and writes about political thought, especially American liberalism.

fields.name: Tayari Jones
fields.description: Jones was born in Atlanta, Georgia, in 1970. She graduated from Spelman College and the University of Iowa, where she received an MFA in fiction writing.

fields.name: Tara Westover
fields.description: Tara Westover is an American memoirist, essayist and historian. Her memoir Educated debuted at No. 1 on The New York Times bestseller list and was a finalist for a number of national awards, including...

fields.name: V.S. Naipaul
fields.description: Sir Vidiadhar Surajprasad Naipaul FRAS TC was a Trinidadian-born British writer of works of fiction and nonfiction in English.

fields.name: Michael Ondaatje
fields.description: Philip Michael Ondaatje CC FRSL is a Sri Lankan-born Canadian poet, fiction writer, essayist, novelist, editor, and filmmaker. Ondaatje's literary career began with his poetry in 1967, publishing The Dainty Monsters, and then in 1970 the critically acclaimed The Collected Works of Billy the Kid.

fields.name: Peter H. Reynolds
fields.description: Peter Hamilton Reynolds is a Canadian author and illustrator of children's books and is the founder of the educational media company FableVision.

fields.name: Henry M. Paulson
fields.description: Henry "Hank" Merritt Paulson Jr. is an American banker and financier who served as the 74th United States Secretary of the Treasury from 2006 to 2009. Prior to his role in the Department of the Treasury, Paulson was the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of major investment bank Goldman Sachs.

fields.name: Peter W. Huber
fields.description: Peter William Huber was a lawyer and author who served as a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute and was a founding partner at the law firm of Kellogg, Huber, Hansen, Todd, Evans & Figel.

fields.name: Bill Gates
fields.description: William Henry Gates III is an American business magnate, investor, and philanthropist. He is best known for co-founding software giant Microsoft, along with his late childhood friend Paul Allen.

fields.name: Jeff Bezos
fields.description: Jeffrey Preston Bezos is an American entrepreneur, media proprietor, investor, and commercial astronaut. He is the founder, executive chairman, and former president and CEO of Amazon, the world's largest e-commerce and cloud computing company.

fields.name: Eula Biss
fields.description: Eula Biss is an American non-fiction writer who is the author of four books. Biss has won the Carl Sandburg Literary Award, the Rona Jaffe Foundation Writers' Award, the Graywolf Press Nonfiction Prize, the Pushcart Prize, and the National Book Critics Circle Award.

fields.name: Daron Acemoglu
fields.description: Kamer Daron Acemoğlu is a Turkish-born American economist who has taught at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology since 1993. He is currently the Elizabeth and James Killian Professor of Economics at MIT. He was named Institute Professor in 2019.

fields.name: Thomas Kuhn
fields.description: Thomas Samuel Kuhn was an American historian and philosopher of science whose 1962 book The Structure of Scientific Revolutions was influential in both academic and popular circles, introducing the term paradigm shift, which has since become an English-language idiom.

fields.name: Moisés Naím
fields.description: Moisés Naím is a Venezuelan journalist and writer. He is a Distinguished Fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. In 2013, the British magazine Prospect listed Naím as one of the world's leading thinkers.

fields.name: Michelle Alexander
fields.description: Michelle Alexander is an American writer and civil rights activist. She is best known for her 2010 book The New Jim Crow: Mass Incarceration in the Age of Colorblindness. Since 2018, she has been an opinion columnist for The New York Times.

fields.name: Leonardo da Vinci
fields.description: Leonardo di ser Piero da Vinci was an Italian polymath of the High Renaissance who was active as a painter, draughtsman, engineer, scientist, theorist, sculptor, and architect.

fields.name: Dan Brown
fields.description: Daniel Gerhard Brown is an American author best known for his thriller novels, including the Robert Langdon novels Angels & Demons, The Da Vinci Code, The Lost Symbol, Inferno, and Origin. His novels are treasure hunts that usually take place over a period of 24 hours

fields.name: Jeremy Heimans,
fields.description: Jeremy Heimans is co-founder and CEO of Purpose and the co-author of New Power: How Power Works in Our Hyperconnected World - and How to Make It Work for You. He has a TED talk on the topic named What new power looks like

fields.name: James Kaplan
fields.description: James C. Kaplan, Jr. is an American novelist, journalist, and biographer.

fields.name: David Fromkin
fields.description: David Henry Fromkin was an American historian, best known for his interpretive account of the Middle East, A Peace to End All Peace, in which he recounts the role European powers played between 1914 and 1922 in creating the modern Middle East.

fields.name: Marcus Luttrell
fields.description: Marcus Luttrell is a retired United States Navy SEAL who received the Navy Cross and Purple Heart for his actions in June 2005 against Taliban fighters during Operation Red Wings in which he was the lone survivor. Luttrell became an SO1 by the end of his eight-year career in the United States Navy.

fields.name: Jerry West
fields.description: Jerome Alan West is an American basketball executive and former player. He played professionally for the Los Angeles Lakers of the National Basketball Association.

fields.name: Matthew Josephson
fields.description: Matthew Josephson was an American journalist and author of works on nineteenth-century French literature and American political and business history of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Josephson popularized the term "robber baron"

fields.name: Fred Brooks
fields.description: Frederick Phillips Brooks Jr. was an American computer architect, software engineer, and computer scientist, best known for managing the development of IBM's System/360 family of computers and the OS/360 ...

fields.name: Joseph Heller
fields.description: Joseph Heller was an American author of novels, short stories, plays, and screenplays. His best-known work is the 1961 novel Catch-22, a satire on war and bureaucracy, whose title has become a synonym for an absurd or contradictory choice. He was nominated in 1972 for the Nobel Prize in Literature.

fields.name: Andrew Grove
fields.description: Andrew Stephen Grove was a Hungarian-American businessman and engineer who served as the third CEO of Intel Corporation. He escaped from Hungarian People's Republic during the 1956 revolution at the age of 20 and moved to the United States, where he finished his education.

fields.name: Will Durant
fields.description: William James Durant was an American historian and philosopher, best known for his 11-volume work, The Story of Civilization, which contains and details the history of Eastern and Western civilizations. It was written in collaboration with his wife, Ariel Durant, and published between 1935 and 1975.

fields.name: Sam Smith
fields.description: Samuel Frederick Smith is an English singer and songwriter. In October 2012, they were featured on Disclosure's breakthrough single "Latch", which peaked at number eleven on the UK Singles Chart. They were featured on Naughty Boy's "La La La", which became a number-one single in May 2013

fields.name: Ernest K. Gann
fields.description: Ernest Kellogg Gann was an American aviator, author, sailor, and conservationist. He is best known for his novels and memoirs about early aviation and nautical adventures.

fields.name: Nikola Tesla
fields.description: Nikola Tesla was a Serbian-American inventor, electrical engineer, mechanical engineer, and futurist best known for his contributions to the design of the modern alternating current electricity supply system.

fields.name: Ben Horowitz
fields.description: Benjamin Abraham Horowitz is an American businessman, investor, blogger, and author. He is a technology entrepreneur and co-founder of the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz along with Marc Andreessen.

fields.name: Neal Stephenson
fields.description: Neal Town Stephenson is an American writer known for his works of speculative fiction. His novels have been categorized as science fiction, historical fiction, cyberpunk, postcyberpunk, and baroque. Stephenson's work explores mathematics, cryptography, linguistics, philosophy, currency, and the history of science.

fields.name: Naval Ravikant
fields.description: Naval Ravikant is an Indian-American entrepreneur and investor. He is the co-founder, chairman and former CEO of AngelList.

fields.name: Richard Feynman
fields.description: Richard Phillips Feynman was an American theoretical physicist, known for his work in the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, the theory of quantum electrodynamics, the physics of the superfluidity of supercooled liquid helium, as well as his work in particle physics for which he proposed the parton model.

fields.name: Daniel Ek
fields.description: Daniel Ek is a Swedish billionaire entrepreneur and technologist. He is the co-founder and CEO of music streaming service Spotify.

fields.name: Paulo Coelho
fields.description: Paulo Coelho de Souza is a Brazilian lyricist and novelist and a member of the Brazilian Academy of Letters since 2002. His novel The Alchemist became an international best-seller and he has published 30 more books since then.

fields.name: Jared Diamond
fields.description: Jared Mason Diamond is an American geographer, historian, ornithologist, and author best known for his popular science books The Third Chimpanzee; Guns, Germs, and Steel; Collapse, The World Until Yesterday, and Upheaval.

fields.name: James C. Collins
fields.description: James C. "Jim" Collins is an American researcher, author, speaker, and consultant focused on the subject of business management and company sustainability and growth.

fields.name: Hamilton W. Helmer
fields.description: Hamilton Helmer has spent his career as a practicing business strategist. at Helmer & Associates (later Deep Strategy), a strategy consulting firm he founded, he has led over 200 strategy projects with ...

fields.name: Stephenie Meyer
fields.description: American novelist and film producer. She is best known for writing the vampire romance series Twilight, which has sold over 160 million copies, with translations into 37 different countries

fields.name: Yuval Noah Harari
fields.description: Yuval Noah Harari is an Israeli public intellectual, historian and professor in the Department of History at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem. He is the author of the popular science bestsellers Sapiens:

fields.name: Laozi
fields.description: Laozi, also romanized as Lao Tzu and various other ways, was a semi-legendary ancient Chinese Taoist philosopher, credited with writing the Tao Te Ching. Laozi is a Chinese honorific, generally translated as "the Old Master".

fields.name: Morgan Housel
fields.description: Morgan Housel

fields.name: James Clear
fields.description: James Clear

fields.name: Miyamoto Musashi
fields.description: Miyamoto Musashi, also known as Shinmen Takezō, Miyamoto Bennosuke or, by his Buddhist name, Niten Dōraku, was a Japanese swordsman, philosopher, strategist, writer and rōnin, who became renowned through stories of his unique double-bladed swordsmanship and undefeated record in his 61 duels.

fields.name: Douglas Adams
fields.description: Douglas Noël Adams was an English author, humorist, and screenwriter, best known for The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy. Originally a 1978 BBC radio comedy, The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy developed into a "trilogy" of five books that sold more than 15 million copies in his lifetime.

fields.name: Douglas Hofstadter
fields.description: Douglas Richard Hofstadter is an American scholar of cognitive science, physics, and comparative literature whose research includes concepts such as the sense of self in relation to the external world, consciousness, analogy-making, artistic creation, literary translation, and discovery in mathematics and physics.

fields.name: Alvin Toffler
fields.description: Alvin Eugene Toffler was an American writer, futurist, and businessman known for his works discussing modern technologies, including the digital revolution and the communication revolution, with emphasis on their effects on cultures worldwide. He is regarded as one of the world's outstanding futurists.

fields.name: Jiddu Krishnamurti
fields.description: Jiddu Krishnamurti was a philosopher, speaker and writer. In his early life, he was raised to be the new World Teacher, an advanced spiritual position in the theosophical tradition, but later rejected this mantle and disbanded the organization setup for that purpose.

fields.name: Roger Zelazny
fields.description: Roger Joseph Zelazny was an American poet and writer of fantasy and science fiction short stories and novels, best known for The Chronicles of Amber.

fields.name: Eric Ries
fields.description: Eric Ries is an American entrepreneur, blogger, and author of The Lean Startup, a book on the lean startup movement. He is also the author of The Startup Way, a book on modern entrepreneurial management.

fields.name: Douglas Murray
fields.description: Douglas Kear Murray is a British author and political commentator. He founded the Centre for Social Cohesion in 2007, which became part of the Henry Jackson Society, where he was associate director from 2011 to 2018.

fields.name: Matt Ridley
fields.description: Matthew White Ridley, 5th Viscount Ridley, DL, FRSL, FMedSci, is a British science writer, journalist and businessman. He is known for his writings on science, the environment, and economics and has been a regular contributor to The Times newspaper.

fields.name: Steven Kotler
fields.description: Steven Kotler is an American author, journalist, and entrepreneur. He is best known for his non-fiction books, including Abundance, A Small Furry Prayer, West of Jesus, Bold, The Rise of Superman, and Stealing Fire.

fields.name: Luis Prieto
fields.description: Eric Robert Walters, CM is a Canadian author of young adult fiction and picture books. As of 2020, Eric Walters has written over 100 books.

fields.name: Amy Chozick
fields.description: Amy Chozick is an American political reporter who works for the New York Times. She is the author of a memoir, Chasing Hillary, about covering Hillary Clinton, and co-wrote an adaptation of the book to the television series, The Girls on the Bus.

fields.name: Chuck Klosterman
fields.description: Charles John Klosterman is an American author and essayist whose work focuses on American popular culture. He has been a columnist for Esquire and ESPN.com and wrote "The Ethicist" column for The New York Times Magazine.

fields.name: James B. Comey
fields.description: James Brien Comey Jr. is an American lawyer who was the seventh director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation from 2013 until his dismissal in May 2017. Comey was a registered Republican for most of his adult life; however, in 2016, he described himself as unaffiliated.

fields.name: Joshua Green
fields.description: Joshua Green is an American journalist who writes primarily on United States politics. He is currently the senior national correspondent at Bloomberg Businessweek. He is a weekly columnist for The Boston Globe and his work has also appeared in The Atlantic.

fields.name: Scott Wapner
fields.description: Scott Wapner is the host of Fast Money: Halftime Report, which airs every weekday on CNBC. Wapner has also reported several documentaries for the network, including Ultimate Fighting: From Blood Sport...

fields.name: Daniel Kahneman
fields.description: Daniel Kahneman is an Israeli-American psychologist and economist notable for his work on the psychology of judgment and decision-making, as well as behavioral economics, for which he was awarded the 2002 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.

fields.name: Jesse Itzler
fields.description: Jesse Itzler is an American entrepreneur, author, and rapper. He is the co-founder of Marquis Jet, one of the largest private jet card companies in the world, a partner in Zico Coconut Water, the founder of The 100 Mile Group, and one of the owners of the NBA's Atlanta Hawks.

fields.name: Fumitake Koga
fields.description: Fumitake Koga is an award-winning professional writer and author. He has released numerous bestselling works of business-related and general non-fiction. He encountered Adlerian psychology in his late twenties and was deeply affected by its conventional wisdom–defying ideas.

fields.name: Ryan Holiday
fields.description: Ryan Holiday is an American author, modern Stoic, public-relations strategist, owner of the Painted Porch Bookshop, and host of the podcast The Daily Stoic. Prior to becoming an author, he served as the former director of marketing and eventually an advisor for American Apparel.

fields.name: Kevin Maney
fields.description: Kevin Maney is a best-selling author and award-winning columnist for Newsweek. Kevin co-authored, with TIBCO CEO Vivek Ranadive, The Two-Second Advantage: How We Succeed by Anticipating the Future...Just Enough. It was a 2011 New York Times bestseller. ...

fields.name: David Goggins
fields.description: David Goggins is an American ultramarathon runner, ultra-distance cyclist, triathlete, public speaker, and author. He is a retired United States Navy SEAL member who served in the Iraq War. His first memoir, Can't Hurt Me, was released in 2018 and a sequel Never Finished in 2022.

fields.name: David Michaelis
fields.description: David Tead Michaelis is an American writer since the late 1970s. As a biographer, Michealis wrote about N.C. Wyeth, Charles Schulz and Eleanor Roosevelt. He won the 1999 Ambassador Book Award in the Autobiography and Biography category with N.C.

fields.name: Nick Hornby
fields.description: Nicholas Peter John Hornby is an English writer and lyricist. He is best known for his memoir Fever Pitch and the novels High Fidelity and About a Boy, all of which were adapted into feature films. Hornby's work frequently touches upon music, sport, and the aimless and obsessive natures of his protagonists.

fields.name: Arnold Ehret
fields.description: Arnold Ehret was a German naturopath and alternative health educator, best known for developing the Mucusless Diet Healing System. Ehret authored books and articles on dieting, detoxification, fruitarianism, fasting, food combining, health, longevity, naturopathy, physical culture and vitalism.

fields.name: Ram Dass
fields.description: Ram Dass, also known as Baba Ram Dass, was an American spiritual teacher, guru of modern yoga, psychologist, and writer. His best-selling 1971 book Be Here Now, which has been described by multiple reviewers as "seminal", helped popularize Eastern spirituality and yoga in the West.

fields.name: Jack Kerouac
fields.description: Jean-Louis Lebris de Kérouac, known as Jack Kerouac, was an American novelist and poet who, alongside William S. Burroughs and Allen Ginsberg, was a pioneer of the Beat Generation. Of French-Canadian ancestry, Kerouac was raised in a French-speaking home in Lowell, Massachusetts.

fields.name: Alan Watts
fields.description: Alan Wilson Watts was an English writer, speaker, and self-styled "philosophical entertainer", known for interpreting and popularising Japanese, Chinese, and Indian traditions of Buddhist, Taoist, and Hindu philosophy for a Western audience.

fields.name: Chögyam Trungpa
fields.description: Chögyam Trungpa was a Tibetan Buddhist meditation master and holder of both the Kagyu and Nyingma lineages of Tibetan Buddhism, the 11th of the Trungpa tülkus, a tertön, supreme abbot of the Surmang ...

fields.name: Edmond Bordeaux Szekely
fields.description: Edmond Bordeaux Szekely was a Hungarian philologist/linguist, philosopher, psychologist, and natural living enthusiast. Szekely authored The Essene Gospel of Peace, which he claimed he had translated from an ancient text he supposedly discovered in the 1920s. Scholars consider the text a forgery.

fields.name: Surendranath Dasgupta
fields.description: Surendranath Dasgupta was an Indian scholar of Sanskrit and Indian philosophy.

fields.name: Paul Williams
fields.description: Paul Hamilton Williams Jr. is an American composer, singer, songwriter, and actor. He is known for writing and co-writing popular songs performed by a number of acts in the 1970s, including Three Dog ...

fields.name: Paul William
fields.description: Paul William Gallico was an American novelist and short story and sports writer. Many of his works were adapted for motion pictures.

fields.name: Vladimir Nabokov
fields.description: Vladimir Vladimirovich Nabokov, also known by the pen name Vladimir Sirin, was an expatriate Russian and Russian-American novelist, poet, translator, and entomologist. Born in Imperial Russia in 1899, Nabokov wrote his first nine novels in Russian while living in Berlin, where he met his wife.

fields.name: Doris Kearns Goodwin
fields.description: Doris Helen Kearns Goodwin is an American biographer, historian, former sports journalist, and political commentator.

fields.name: Rick Tetzeli
fields.description: RICK TETZELI, the executive editor of Fast Company, has covered technology for two decades. He is the former deputy editor of Fortune and editor of Entertainment Weekly.

fields.name: Robb Wolf
fields.description: Robb Wolf, a former research biochemist is the two-time New York Times/Wall Street Journal bestselling author of The Paleo Solution and Wired To Eat. Robb has transformed the lives of hundreds of thousands of people around the world via his top-ranked iTunes podcast, books, and seminars. ...

fields.name: Atul Gawande
fields.description: Atul Atmaram Gawande is an American surgeon, writer, and public health researcher. He practices general and endocrine surgery at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, Massachusetts.

fields.name: Steve Jamison
fields.description: Steve Jamison collaborated with legendary UCLA coach John Wooden on the national bestseller Wooden on Leadership. He lives in San Francisco, California. Visit his website at SteveJamison.com.

fields.name: Ta-Nehisi Coates
fields.description: Ta-Nehisi Paul Coates is an American author and journalist. He gained a wide readership during his time as a national correspondent at The Atlantic, where he wrote about cultural, social, and political issues, particularly regarding African Americans and white supremacy.

fields.name: Colin Woodard
fields.description: Colin Woodard is an American journalist and writer known for his books American Nations: A History of the Eleven Rival Regional Cultures of North America, The Republic of Pirates, and The Lobster Coast, a cultural and environmental history of coastal Maine.

fields.name: Lawrence Weschler
fields.description: Lawrence Weschler is an author of works of creative nonfiction. A graduate of Cowell College of the University of California, Santa Cruz, Weschler was for over twenty years a staff writer at The New Yorker, where his work shuttled between political tragedies and cultural comedies.

fields.name: Isaiah Jackson
fields.description: Isaiah Ju'mar Jackson is an American basketball player for the Indiana Pacers of the National Basketball Association. He played college basketball for the Kentucky Wildcats.

fields.name: Don Miguel Ruiz
fields.description: Miguel Ángel Ruiz Macías, better known as Don Miguel Ruiz, is a Mexican author of Toltec spiritual and neo-shamanistic texts. His work is best received among members of the New Thought movement that focuses on ancient teachings as a means to achieve spiritual enlightenment.

fields.name: Mikhail Bulgakov
fields.description: Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov was a Russian, later Soviet writer, medical doctor, and playwright active in the first half of the 20th century. He is best known for his novel The Master and Margarita, published posthumously, which has been called one of the masterpieces of the 20th century.

fields.name: Gloria Steinem
fields.description: Gloria Marie Steinem is an American journalist and social-political activist who emerged as a nationally recognized leader of second-wave feminism in the United States in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Steinem was a columnist for New York magazine and a co-founder of Ms. magazine.

fields.name: Howard C. Cutler
fields.description: Howard C. Cutler is an American writer and psychiatrist who practices in Phoenix, Arizona. He is an expert in the science of human happiness and co-wrote The Art of Happiness with the 14th Dalai Lama. Cutler has been interviewed by Time and O, The Oprah Magazine, as well as hundreds of radio and television programs.

fields.name: Daniel Quinn
fields.description: Daniel Clarence Quinn was an American author, cultural critic, and publisher of educational texts, best known for his novel Ishmael, which won the Turner Tomorrow Fellowship Award in 1991 and was published the following year.

fields.name: Bryan Mealer
fields.description: BRYAN MEALER is the author of Muck City: Winning and Losing in Football’s Forgotten Town and the New York Times bestseller The Boy Who Harnessed the Wind, which he wrote with William Kamkwamba, in addition to the children’s book of the same title...

fields.name: Daphne du Maurier
fields.description: Dame Daphne du Maurier, Lady Browning, DBE was an English novelist, biographer, and playwright. Her parents were actor-manager Sir Gerald du Maurier and his wife, actress Muriel Beaumont. Her grandfather was George du Maurier, a writer and cartoonist.

fields.name: F. Scott Fitzgerald
fields.description: Francis Scott Key Fitzgerald was an American novelist, essayist, and short story writer. He is best known for his novels depicting the flamboyance and excess of the Jazz Age—a term he popularized in his short story collection Tales of the Jazz Age.

fields.name: Jerry Spinelli
fields.description: Jerry Spinelli is an American writer of children's novels that feature adolescence and early adulthood. His novels include Maniac Magee, Stargirl, and Wringer.

fields.name: Sally Rooney
fields.description: Sally Rooney is an Irish author and screenwriter. She has published three novels: Conversations with Friends, Normal People, and Beautiful World, Where Are You. The former two were adapted into the television miniseries Normal People and Conversations with Friends.

fields.name: Sam Kashner
fields.description: Sam Kashner and his wife Nancy Schoenberger are creative writing teachers at William and Mary College. ..

fields.name: Laurence Leamer
fields.description: Laurence Leamer is an American author and journalist. Leamer is a former Ford Fellow in International Development at the University of Oregon and a former International Fellow at Columbia University.

fields.name: Elizabeth Gilbert
fields.description: Elizabeth Gilbert is an American journalist and author. She is best known for her 2006 memoir, Eat, Pray, Love, which has sold over 12 million copies and has been translated into over 30 languages. The book was also made into a film of the same name in 2010.

fields.name: E. B. White
fields.description: Elwyn Brooks White was an American writer. He was the author of several highly popular books for children, including Stuart Little, Charlotte's Web, and The Trumpet of the Swan. In a 2012 survey of School Library Journal readers, Charlotte's Web came in first in their poll of the top one hundred children's novels.

fields.name: Harper Lee
fields.description: Nelle Harper Lee was an American novelist. She wrote the 1960 novel To Kill a Mockingbird which won the 1961 Pulitzer Prize and became a classic of modern American literature.

fields.name: Andy Weir
fields.description: Andrew Taylor Weir /wir/ is an American novelist and former computer programmer. His 2011 novel The Martian was adapted into the 2015 film of the same name directed by Ridley Scott.

fields.name: Nick Lane
fields.description: Nick Lane is a British biochemist and writer. He is a professor in evolutionary biochemistry at University College London. He has published five books to date which have won several awards.

fields.name: Kevin Kelly
fields.description: Kevin Kelly is the founding executive editor of Wired magazine and a former editor/publisher of the Whole Earth Review. He has also been a writer, photographer, conservationist, and student of Asian and digital culture.

fields.name: Virginia Postrel
fields.description: Virginia Inman Postrel is an American political and cultural writer of broadly libertarian, or classical liberal, views. She is a recipient of the Bastiat Prize.

fields.name: Sheridan Anne
fields.description: Sheridan Anne is the author of all things twisted, dark, and just a little messed up. She writes mainly Dark Contemporary Romance and has been known to dabble in the Fantasy world and more recently, diving headfirst into Reverse Harem.

fields.name: Bjørn Lomborg
fields.description: Bjørn Lomborg is a Danish author and the president of the think tank Copenhagen Consensus Center. He is the former director of the Danish government's Environmental Assessment Institute in Copenhagen. He became internationally known for his best-selling and controversial book The Skeptical Environmentalist.

fields.name: Andrew Montford
fields.description: Andrew William Montford is a British writer and editor who is the owner of the Bishop Hill blog. He is the author of The Hockey Stick Illusion.

fields.name: Sue Armstrong
fields.description: Sue Armstrong is a science writer and broadcaster.  As a foreign correspondent based in Brussels and then South Africa, she worked for (amongst others) New Scientist magazine and the BBC World Service radio.

fields.name: Gerald Durrell
fields.description: Gerald Malcolm Durrell, OBE was a British naturalist, writer, zookeeper, conservationist, and television presenter. He founded the Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust and the Jersey Zoo on the Channel Island of Jersey in 1959.

fields.name: Julian Simon
fields.description: Julian Lincoln Simon was an American professor of business administration at the University of Maryland and a Senior Fellow at the Cato Institute at the time of his death, after previously serving as a longtime economics and business professor at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.

fields.name: David Baldacci
fields.description: David Baldacci is an American novelist. An attorney by education, Baldacci writes mainly suspense novels and legal thrillers.

fields.name: Anthony Doerr
fields.description: Anthony Doerr is an American author of novels and short stories. He gained widespread recognition for his 2014 novel All the Light We Cannot See, which won the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.

fields.name: Gareth Williams
fields.description: Gareth Wyn Williams was a Welsh mathematician and Junior Analyst for GCHQ seconded to the Secret Intelligence Service who was found dead in suspicious circumstances at a Security Service safe house flat in Pimlico, London, on 23 August 2010.

fields.name: Charles Darwin
fields.description: Charles Robert Darwin FRS FRGS FLS FZS JP was an English naturalist, geologist, and biologist, widely known for his contributions to evolutionary biology. His proposition that all species of life have descended from a common ancestor is now generally accepted and considered a fundamental concept in science.

fields.name: Rory Sutherland
fields.description: Rory Sutherland is the Vice Chairman of Ogilvy UK and the founder of the behavioral science practice. He writes the Spectator's 'Wiki Man' column, presents a series for BBC Radio 4, serves on the advisory board of The Evolution Institute, and is the former President of the IPA (Institute of Practitioners in Advertising). ...

fields.name: Wade Davis
fields.description: Edmund Wade Davis CM is a Canadian cultural anthropologist, ethnobotanist, author, and photographer. Davis came to prominence with his 1985 best-selling book The Serpent and the Rainbow about the zombies of Haiti.

fields.name: Bill Browder
fields.description: William Felix Browder is an American-born British financier and political activist. He is the CEO and co-founder of Hermitage Capital Management, the investment advisor to the Hermitage Fund, which at one time was the largest foreign portfolio investor in Russia.

fields.name: David G. Schwartz
fields.description: David G. Schwartz, the Director of the Center for Gaming Research and instructor at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas, studies gambling and casinos, Las Vegas, tourism, and games...

fields.name: Alan Paton
fields.description: Alan Stewart Paton was a South African writer and anti-apartheid activist. His works include the novels Cry, the Beloved Country, Too Late the Phalarope, and the narrative poem The Wasteland.

fields.name: Rohinton Mistry
fields.description: Rohinton Mistry CM is an Indian-born Canadian writer. He has been the recipient of many awards including the Neustadt International Prize for Literature in 2012. Each of his first three novels was shortlisted for the Booker Prize.

fields.name: Lalita Tademy
fields.description: Lalita Tademy's first novel, CANE RIVER, was chosen by Oprah Winfrey for her summer book pick and became a New York Times bestseller for seventeen weeks. She lives and writes in Menlo Park, California.

fields.name: Colson Whitehead
fields.description: Arch Colson Chipp Whitehead is an American novelist. He is the author of eight novels, including his 1999 debut work The Intuitionist; The Underground Railroad, for which he won the 2016 National Book ...

fields.name: Uwem Akpan
fields.description: Uwem Akpan is a Nigerian writer. He is the author of Say You're One of Them, a collection of five stories published by Little, Brown & Company. The book inspired Angelique Kidjo to write the song "Agbalagba". It made the Best of the Year list in People magazine, The Wall Street Journal, and other places.

fields.name: Imbolo Mbue
fields.description: Imbolo Mbue is a Cameroonian-American novelist and short-story writer based in New York City. She is known for her debut novel Behold the Dreamers, which has garnered her the PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction and the Blue Metropolis Words to Change Award.

fields.name: Toni Morrison
fields.description: Chloe Anthony Wofford Morrison, known as Toni Morrison, was an American novelist. Her first novel, The Bluest Eye, was published in 1970. The critically acclaimed Song of Solomon brought her national attention and won the National Book Critics Circle Award.

fields.name: Robert Kolker
fields.description: Robert Kolker is an American journalist who worked as a contributing editor at New York Magazine and a former projects and investigations reporter for Bloomberg News and Bloomberg Businessweek.

fields.name: Sue Monk Kidd
fields.description: Sue Monk Kidd is an American writer from Sylvester, Georgia best known for her novels The Secret Life of Bees and The Invention of Wings.

fields.name: Jeanine Cummins
fields.description: Jeanine Cummins is an American author of Irish and Puerto Rican heritage. She has written four books: a memoir titled A Rip in Heaven and three novels, The Outside Boy, The Crooked Branch, and American Dirt. American Dirt was a notable success, selling over 3 million copies in 37 languages.

fields.name: Gabriel García Márquez
fields.description: Gabriel José de la Concordia García Márquez was a Colombian novelist, short-story writer, screenwriter, and journalist, known affectionately as Gabo or Gabito throughout Latin America.

fields.name: Christina Schwarz
fields.description: Christina Schwarz grew up in Wisconsin and currently lives in Los Angeles. She contributes regularly to The Atlantic Monthly and writes an audiobook column for the San Francisco Chronicle Book Review. She is at work on her second novel.

fields.name: Jonathan Franzen
fields.description: Jonathan Earl Franzen is an American novelist and essayist. His 2001 novel The Corrections, a sprawling, satirical family drama, drew widespread critical acclaim, and earned Franzen a National Book Award...

fields.name: David Wroblewski
fields.description: David Wroblewski is an American novelist whose first novel was The Story of Edgar Sawtelle.

fields.name: Malika Oufkir
fields.description: Malika Oufkir is a Moroccan Berber writer and former "disappeared". She is the daughter of General Mohamed Oufkir and a cousin of fellow Moroccan writer and actress Leila Shenna.

fields.name: John Steinbeck
fields.description: John Ernst Steinbeck was an American writer. He won the 1962 Nobel Prize in Literature "for his realistic and imaginative writings, combining as they do sympathetic humor and keen social perception". He has been called "a giant of American letters."

fields.name: Bob Roth
fields.description: Bob Roth is an American Transcendental Meditation teacher and author. He is the CEO of the David Lynch Foundation and a director of the Center for Leadership Performance.

fields.name: Joyce Carol Oates
fields.description: Joyce Carol Oates is an American writer. Oates published her first book in 1963, and has since published 58 novels, a number of plays and novellas, and many volumes of short stories, poetry, and non-fiction.

fields.name: Elizabeth Strout
fields.description: Elizabeth Strout is an American novelist and author. She is widely known for her works in literary fiction and her descriptive characterization.

fields.name: Glennon Doyle
fields.description: Glennon Doyle is an American author and activist known for her books Untamed, Love Warrior, and Carry On, Warrior.

fields.name: Carson McCullers
fields.description: Carson McCullers was an American novelist, short-story writer, playwright, essayist, and poet. Her first novel, The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter, explores the spiritual isolation of misfits and outcasts in a small town in the Southern United States. Her other novels have similar themes and most are set in the Deep South.

fields.name: Ann-Marie MacDonald
fields.description: Ann-Marie MacDonald OC is a Canadian playwright, author, actress, and broadcast host who lives in Toronto, Ontario. MacDonald is the daughter of a member of Canada's military; she was born at an air force base near Baden-Baden, West Germany. She is of partial Lebanese descent through her mother.

fields.name: Jeffrey Eugenides
fields.description: Jeffrey Kent Eugenides is an American novelist and short story writer. He has written numerous short stories and essays, as well as three novels: The Virgin Suicides, Middlesex, and The Marriage Plot.

fields.name: Leo Tolstoy
fields.description: Count Lev Nikolayevich Tolstoy, usually referred to in English as Leo Tolstoy, was a Russian writer who is regarded as one of the greatest authors of all time.

fields.name: Sidney Poitier
fields.description: Sidney Poitier KBE was a Bahamian and American actor, film director, and diplomat. In 1964, he was the first Black actor and the first Bahamian to win the Academy Award for Best Actor.

fields.name: Elie Wiesel
fields.description: Elie Wiesel was a Romanian-born American writer, professor, political activist, Nobel laureate, and Holocaust survivor. He authored 57 books, written mostly in French and English, including Night, a work based on his experiences as a Jewish prisoner in the Auschwitz and Buchenwald concentration camps.

fields.name: Melinda Haynes
fields.description: Melinda Haynes is an American novelist. She grew up in Hattiesburg, Mississippi. For much of her adult life, she was a painter. In 1999, she wrote her first published novel, Mother of Pearl, while living in a mobile home in Grand Bay, Alabama. Melinda Haynes currently resides in Mobile, Alabama with her husband, Ray.

fields.name: Charles Dickens
fields.description: Charles John Huffam Dickens was an English writer and social critic who created some of the world's best-known fictional characters and is regarded by many as the greatest novelist of the Victorian era.

fields.name: James Frey
fields.description: James Frey is an American writer and businessman. His first two books, A Million Little Pieces and My Friend Leonard were bestsellers marketed as memoirs. Large parts of the stories were later found to be exaggerated or fabricated, sparking a media controversy.

fields.name: Maya Angelou
fields.description: Maya Angelou was an American memoirist, poet, and civil rights activist. She published seven autobiographies, three books of essays, several books of poetry, and is credited with a list of plays, movies, and television shows spanning over 50 years. She received dozens of awards and more than 50 honorary degrees.

fields.name: Jane Hamilton
fields.description: Jane Hamilton is an American novelist. She was born in Oak Park, Illinois, in 1957.

fields.name: Ernest J. Gaines
fields.description: Ernest James Gaines was an American author whose works have been taught in college classrooms and translated into many languages, including French, Spanish, German, Russian, and Chinese. Four of his works were made into television movies.

fields.name: Sue Miller
fields.description: Sue Miller is an American novelist and short story writer who has written a number of best-selling novels.

fields.name: Pearl Cleage
fields.description: Pearl Cleage is an African-American playwright, essayist, novelist, poet, and political activist. She is currently the Playwright in Residence at the Alliance Theatre and at the Just Us Theater Company. Cleage is a political activist.

fields.name: Edwidge Danticat
fields.description: Edwidge Danticat is a Haitian-American novelist and short story writer. Her first novel, Breath, Eyes, Memory, was published in 1994 and went on to become an Oprah's Book Club selection. Danticat has since written or edited several books and has been the recipient of many awards and honors.

fields.name: Ayana Mathis
fields.description: Ayana Mathis is a graduate of the Iowa Writers' Workshop and is a recipient of the Michener-Copernicus Fellowship. The Twelve Tribes of Hattie, her first novel and a New York Times bestseller, was chosen by Oprah Winfrey as the second selection for Oprah's Book Club 2.0. She lives and writes in Brooklyn.

fields.name: Gwyn Hyman Rubio
fields.description: Gwyn Hyman Rubio is an American author, best known for her novel Icy Sparks.

fields.name: William Faulkner
fields.description: William Cuthbert Faulkner was an American writer known for his novels and short stories set in the fictional Yoknapatawpha County, based in Lafayette County, Mississippi, where Faulkner spent most of his life.

fields.name: Bernhard Schlink
fields.description: Bernhard Schlink is a German lawyer, academic, and novelist. He is best known for his novel The Reader, which was first published in 1995 and became an international bestseller. He won the 2014 Park Kyong-ni Prize.

fields.name: Billie Letts
fields.description: Billie Dean Letts was an American novelist and educator. She was a professor at Southeastern Oklahoma State University.

fields.name: Elizabeth Berg
fields.description: Elizabeth Berg is an American novelist. Berg was born in Saint Paul, Minnesota, USA, and lived in Boston prior to her residence in Chicago. She studied English and Humanities at the University of Minnesota but later ended up with a nursing degree.

fields.name: Bret Lott
fields.description: Bret Lott is the New York Times author and professor of English at the College of Charleston. He is Crazyhorse magazine's nonfiction editor and leads a study abroad program every summer to Spoleto, Italy. Lott was appointed to the National Council of the Arts by President George W. Bush and served a six-year term.

fields.name: Andre Dubus III
fields.description: Andre Dubus III is an American novelist and short story writer. He is a member of the faculty at the University of Massachusetts Lowell.

fields.name: Anita Shreve
fields.description: Anita Hale Shreve was an American writer, chiefly known for her novels. One of her first published stories, Past the Island, Drifting, was awarded an O. Henry Prize in 1976.

fields.name: Bill Cosby
fields.description: William Henry Cosby Jr. is an American comedian, actor, and media personality. He has made significant contributions to American and African-American culture and gained a reputation as "America's Dad" for his portrayal of Cliff Huxtable on The Cosby Show.

fields.name: Ursula Hegi
fields.description: Ursula Hegi is a German-born American writer. She is currently an instructor in the MFA program at Stony Brook Southampton. She was born Ursula Koch in 1946 in Düsseldorf, Germany, a city that was heavily bombed during World War II.

fields.name: Mary McGarry Morris
fields.description: Mary McGarry Morris is an American novelist, short story author, and playwright from New England. She uses its towns as settings for her works.

fields.name: Sheri Reynolds
fields.description: Sheri Reynolds is an author of contemporary Southern fiction. She was born and raised in rural South Carolina and lives on Virginia's eastern shore. She graduated from Conway High School in 1985, Davidson College in 1989, and Virginia Commonwealth University in 1992.

fields.name: Robert Morgan
fields.description: Robert Morgan is an American poet, short story writer, and novelist.

fields.name: Kaye Gibbons

fields.name: Isabel Allende
fields.description: Isabel Angélica Allende Llona is a Chilean writer. Allende, whose works sometimes contain aspects of the genre magical realism, is known for novels such as The House of the Spirits and City of the Beasts, which have been commercially successful.

fields.name: Sean Kelly
fields.description: John James 'Sean' Kelly is an Irish former professional road bicycle racer, one of the most successful road cyclists of the 1980s, and one of the finest Classics riders of all time.

fields.name: Chris Bohjalian
fields.description: Chris A. Bohjalian is an Armenian-American novelist and the author of 20 novels, including Midwives, The Sandcastle Girls, The Guest Room, and The Flight Attendant.

fields.name: Alice Hoffman
fields.description: Alice Hoffman is an American novelist and young-adult and children's writer, best known for her 1995 novel Practical Magic, which was adapted for a 1998 film of the same name.

fields.name: Anna Quindlen
fields.description: Anna Marie Quindlen is an American author, journalist, and opinion columnist. Her New York Times column, Public and Private, won the Pulitzer Prize for Commentary in 1992.

fields.name: Michael Alan Singer
fields.description: Michael Alan "Mickey" Singer is an American author, journalist, motivational speaker, and former software developer.

fields.name: Abdulrazak Gurnah

fields.name: Tawni O'Dell
fields.description: Tawni O'Dell is an American novelist. Her first published novel, Back Roads, was selected by Oprah Winfrey for Oprah's Book Club in March 2000.

fields.name: Breena Clarke

fields.name: Robert Bartlett

fields.name: William H. McNeill
fields.description: William Hardy McNeill was an American historian and author, noted for his argument that contact and exchange among civilizations is what drives human history forward, first postulated in The Rise of the West.

fields.name: William Finnegan

fields.name: Elizabeth Kolbert

fields.name: Naomi Alderman

fields.name: Bono
fields.description: Paul David Hewson, known by the nickname Bono, is an Irish singer-songwriter, activist, and philanthropist.

fields.name: Amor Towles

fields.description: George Saunders is an American writer of short stories, essays, novellas, children's books, and novels.

fields.name: Allie Brosh
fields.description: Allie Brosh is an American blogger, writer, and comic artist best known for her blog in the form of a webcomic Hyperbole and a Half. Brosh grew up in small towns across the U.S. before attending the University of Montana.

fields.name: Jill Lepore
fields.description: Jill Lepore is an American historian and journalist. She is the David Woods Kemper '41 Professor of American History at Harvard University and a staff writer at The New Yorker, where she has contributed since 2005.

fields.name: Jeremy N. Smith
fields.description: JEREMY N. SMITH has written for the New York Times, the Atlantic, and Discover, among other outlets, and he and his work have been featured by CNN, NPR News, and Wired. A graduate of Harvard College and the University of Montana, he is the author of Growing a Garden City and Epic Measures.

fields.name: Steven Levitt
fields.description: Steven David Levitt is an American economist and co-author of the best-selling book Freakonomics and its sequels.

fields.name: John Brooks
fields.description: John Brooks was a writer and longtime contributor to The New Yorker magazine, where he worked for many years as a staff writer, specializing in financial topics.

fields.name: Jordan Peterson

fields.name: Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn
fields.description: Aleksandr Isayevich Solzhenitsyn was a Russian writer.

fields.name: Ernest Becker
fields.description: Ernest Becker was an American cultural anthropologist and author of the 1974 Pulitzer Prize-winning book, The Denial of Death.

fields.name: Viktor Frankl
fields.description: Viktor Emil Frankl was a Jewish-Austrian psychiatrist and holocaust survivor, who founded logotherapy, a school of psychotherapy that describes a search for a life's meaning as the central human motivational force.

fields.name: Steven Pressfield
fields.description: Steven Pressfield is an American author of historical fiction, non-fiction, and screenplays, including his 1995 novel The Legend of Bagger Vance and 2002 non-fiction book The War of Art.

fields.name: joe rogan
fields.description: Joseph James Rogan is an American UFC color commentator, podcaster, comedian, actor, and former television presenter.

fields.name: Ursula K. Le Guin
fields.description: Ursula Kroeber Le Guin was an American author best known for her works of speculative fiction, including science fiction works set in her Hainish universe, and the Earthsea fantasy series.

fields.name: stephen king
fields.description: Stephen Edwin King is an American author of horror, supernatural fiction, suspense, crime, science-fiction, and fantasy novels.

fields.name: Aravind Adiga
fields.description: Aravind Adiga is an Indian writer and journalist. His debut novel, The White Tiger, won the 2008 Man Booker Prize.

fields.name: Cormac Mc Carthy

fields.name: Donna Tartt
fields.description: Donna Louise Tartt is an American novelist and essayist. Her work has been widely critically-acclaimed, and her novel The Goldfinch won the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction and has been adapted into a film.

fields.name: Thomas Sowell
fields.description: Thomas Sowell is an American economist, author, and social commentator who is a senior fellow at the Hoover Institution.

fields.name: Milton Friedman

fields.name: Ben Shapiro

fields.description: James Michael Surowiecki is an American journalist. He was a staff writer at The New Yorker, where he wrote a regular column on business and finance called "The Financial Page".
